\begin_layout Subsection
Quantum Chromodynamics (QCD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 1950s, a large number of strongly interacting particles (hadrons)
 were discovered in particle physics experiments.
 To understand and explained the spectrum of these particles, in 1963, Gell-Mann
 and Zweig proposed a model in terms of elementary constituents called 
\emph on
quarks.
 
\emph default
The hadrons could be sorted into groups having similar quantum properties
 by the existence of three flavors of quarks inside hadrons.
 Mesons were expected to be quark-antiquark bound states, while baryons
 were interpreted as bound states of three quarks.
 To explain the electric charges and other quantum numbers of hadrons, Gell-Mann
 and Zweig assumed three species of quarks, up (
\emph on
u
\emph default
), down (
\emph on
d
\emph default
) and strange (
\emph on
s
\emph default
).
 With the discovery of more hadrons, the quarks family were extended of
 three more species: charm (
\emph on
c
\emph default
), bottom (
\emph on
b
\emph default
) and top (
\emph on
t
\emph default
).
 To make baryons with integer charges, the quarks were assigned fractional
 electric charge: +2/3 for 
\emph on
u
\emph default
, 
\emph on
c, t, 
\emph default
and -1/3 for 
\emph on
d
\emph default
, 
\emph on
s
\emph default
, 
\emph on
b.
 
\emph default
And all quarks were assumed to be spin-1/2.
 The quark model had great success in predicting new hadronic states, but
 some hadrons composed with three identical quarks with parallel spin, such
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta^{++}$
\end_inset

(
\emph on
uuu
\emph default
), are forbidden by the Pauli exclusion principle.
 To solve this problem, Han and Nambu, Greenberg, and Gell-Mann introduced
 an additional SU(3) gauge degree of freedom of quarks called 
\emph on
color 
\emph default
and an octet of vector gauge bosons called gluons to carry the interaction
 between quarks.
 In 1972, Gell-Man and Fritzsch introduced the Quantum Chromodynamics (QCD)
 to describe the strong interaction between the colored quarks and gluons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The QCD Lagrangian can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L_{{\rm QCD}}}=-\frac{1}{4}F_{a}^{\mu\nu}F_{\mu\nu}^{a}+\underset{f}{\sum}\bar{q_{f}}^{i}i\gamma^{\mu}(D_{\mu})_{ij}q_{f}^{j}-\underset{f}{\sum}m_{f}\bar{q}_{f}^{i}q_{f}^{i}\label{eq:LQCD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{a}^{\mu\nu}=\partial^{\mu}G_{a}^{\nu}-\partial^{\nu}G_{a}^{\mu}+g_{s}f^{abc}G_{b}^{\mu}G_{c}^{\nu}\label{eq:fieldStr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{\mu}=\partial^{\mu}-ig_{s}\frac{\lambda^{a}}{2}G_{a}^{\mu}\label{eq:cd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the QCD coupling constant, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{abc}$
\end_inset

 are the structure constants of the 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(3)_{C}$
\end_inset

 algebra.
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f}^{i}$
\end_inset

 defines a quark field with color 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 and flavor 
\emph on
f 
\emph default
, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are the Dirac matrices.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{a}^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 are the field strengths tensor which were introduced to describe the self
 interaction of the gluon fields.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are the covariant derivative with the Gell-Mann matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{a}$
\end_inset

 and the Yang-Mills (gluon) fields 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\mu}^{a}(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=$
\end_inset

1, 2, ..., 8.
\end_layout

