\begin_layout Subsection
Restoration of the chiral symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another feature of the hot and density strongly interacting matter is the
 restoration of the chiral symmetry.
 Considering the chiral quark-antiquark condensate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \bar{\psi}\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ptxs"

\end_inset

 right panel shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \bar{\psi}\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as and its temperature derivative as a function of the lattice coupling
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=6/g^{2}$
\end_inset

 (a value corresponding to the temperature).
 The nonvanishing chiral condensate at T = 0 spontaneously breaks the chiral
 symmetry and generates a dynamic mass of order 300 MeV for up and down
 quarks.
 With the temperature increasing, the dynamically generated mass melts away
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{cr}$
\end_inset

, and the quarks mass become vanishing again above 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{cr}$
\end_inset

, or in another word, the approximate chiral symmetry is restored.
 Numerical computations of the lattice-discretized path integral for QCD
 at finite temperature predict chiral symmetry restoration to happen at
 a critical temperature of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}\approx160-190$
\end_inset

 MeV, corresponding to an energy density of about 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{c}\approx1{\rm GeV/fm^{3}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.74.054507,Aoki200646"

\end_inset

.
 If considering the quark component in real world (two light quarks 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, and a much heavier strange quarks), this transition is more likely a rapid
 cross-over.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chiral symmetry restoration can be characterized by the rapid decrease of
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}q$
\end_inset

 condensate, while in experiment, the key manifestations are its consequences
 for the hadron spectrum.
 Chiral partners must degenerate which lead to a massive medium modifications
 of hadronic spectral functions as the transition is approached.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 meson is a unique tool for characterizing the chiral properties of hot
 and density medium, since its life time is much short (~1.3 fm) than the
 medium (~10 fm).
 Its spectral functions is expected to be significant modified (comparing
 to other light mesons) during the interaction with medium.
 There are two main scenarios on the in medium modification of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 meson.
 Brown and Rho suggests that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

-meson mass should drop to almost zero as a consequence of chiral symmetry
 restoration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.66.2720,Brown1996333"

\end_inset

.
 Subsequently, more medium modifications of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

